fields.description:
When uploading an attachment to a Confluence page anonymously, this information is stored in the user access log (if enabled):
{code:java}
2018-01-25 14:31:50,939 INFO [http-nio-8090-exec-12] [atlassian.confluence.util.AccessLogFilter] doFilter - POST http://BASEURL/pages/doattachfile.action 
{code}
However, when using the API to add an attachment to a page anonymously, nothing is logged in access log. Call used to add the attachment (which is correctly added to the page):
{code:java}
 curl -v -S -X POST -H "X-Atlassian-Token: nocheck" -F "file=@file2.txt" http://BASEURL/rest/api/content/65537/child/attachment
{code}
*Expected behavior:* Access log to store the information just like it does when using the UI.

Confluence is currently running with embedded Crowd 2.10.2:
{code}
$ git show confluence-project-6.4.3:pom.xml | grep '<crowd.version>'
        <crowd.version>2.10.2</crowd.version>
{code}

In order to avoid issues like [CONFSERVER-54786|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-54786], it would be interesting to upgrade Confluence to use embedded Crowd 2.12.x or the latest version. I am sure that the application would also benefit of new features released in the more recent versions of Crowd as well.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-24502].
  {panel}

It doesn't seem to be possible to change the text alignment using the keyboard in the RTE. I'd expect ctrl-L, ctrl-E and ctrl-R to work as they do in standard word processing applications, but this is not the case.

I can't see the text-alignment options listed at all in the _Keyboard Shortcuts_ dialog either..

Oracle Java recommends that users choose a *Critical Patch Update (CPU)* release of Java rather than a *Patch Set Update (PSU)* release for general usage unless specifically impacted by a bug that is fixed in the PSU. Quoting relevant content from [Oracle's documentation|http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/cpu-psu-explained-2331472.html]:
{quote}
h4. Which Java version should I choose: the CPU or the PSU?
Oracle strongly recommends that all Java SE users upgrade to the latest CPU release available for a release family. Most users should choose the CPU release.

Users should only use the corresponding PSU release if they are being impacted by one of the additional bugs fixed in that version as noted in the release notes.
{quote}

{quote}
h4. What is the difference between a Java CPU and PSU release?
Java SE Critical Patch Updates (CPU) contain fixes to security vulnerabilities and critical bug fixes.

Java SE Patch Set Updates (PSU) contain all of fixes in the corresponding CPU, as well as additional non-critical fixes. Java PSU releases should only be used if you are being impacted by one of the additional bugs fixed in that version.
{quote}

Our [Supported Platforms documentation|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/supported-platforms-207488198.html] does not currently make this distinction. This proposal is to specifically add the verbiage favoring Java CPU releases into our Supported Platforms page.
